<subsection xml:id="subsec-midpoints-of-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Midpoints of Vectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p>
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                        <p>Determine the midpoint of a vector in different situations</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
            <li component="lesson-plan">Grade Level: 10</li>
            <li component="lesson-plan">Estimated Duration: 40 minutes</li>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Know</title>
                        <p>The midpoint of a vector is found by averaging the <m>x</m>-coordinates and <m>y</m>-coordinates: <m>M = \left(\frac{x_1+x_2}{2},\,\frac{y_1+y_2}{2}\right)</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Do</title>
                        <p>Plot endpoints on a coordinate plane, locate midpoints by counting and by formula, and apply the vector derivation <m>\mathbf{OM} = \frac{\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}}{2}</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Apply</title>
                        <p>Use vector midpoints to solve real-life problems in navigation, route planning, and geometry.</p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/midpoints-of-vectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_midpoints-of-vectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Anchor Activity — Discovering Vector Midpoints</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <em>Objective:</em> Students plot points, draw vectors, find midpoints by counting units,
            and discover the midpoint formula by averaging <m>x</m>-coordinates and <m>y</m>-coordinates.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Guiding Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>What are the coordinates of Point <m>A</m>?</li>
                <li>What are the coordinates of Point <m>B</m>?</li>
                <li>How many units are between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> horizontally?</li>
                <li>Where is the midpoint <m>M</m> located?</li>
                <li>What are the coordinates of <m>M</m>?</li>
                <li>How did you find the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>M</m>? (Average of <m>x</m>-coordinates)</li>
                <li>How did you find the <m>y</m>-coordinate of <m>M</m>? (Average of <m>y</m>-coordinates)</li>
                <li>Can you write a formula for finding the midpoint of any two points?</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Circulate among students, ensuring they plot points correctly and identify midpoints accurately.</li>
                <li>Ask probing questions: <q>How did you find the midpoint? What pattern do you see?</q></li>
                <li>For struggling students: <q>Let us count together. <m>A</m> is at <m>(2,3)</m> and <m>B</m> is at <m>(8,3)</m>. What is halfway between 2 and 8?</q></li>
                <li>For early finishers: <q>Try another vector with different <m>y</m>-coordinates. Does your formula still work?</q></li>
                <li>Guide students to articulate: <q>The midpoint <m>x</m>-coordinate is the average of the two <m>x</m>-coordinates, and the midpoint <m>y</m>-coordinate is the average of the two <m>y</m>-coordinates.</q></li>
                <li>Identify 2–3 students with clear findings to share with the class.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <!-- <p xml:id="auto_ieyz8ibp">
        To determine the coordinates of the midpoint <m>\mathbf{M}</m> 
        of the line segment <m>\mathbf{AB}</m> , we can utilize vector operations.
    </p> -->
    <activity xml:id="auto_w40udzhp">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_3sh977su">
            <p xml:id="auto_wfvy6sqm">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_u1to99wk">
                <alert>What you require:</alert> Graph paper
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_7je2ucex">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_y67zdhcy">
                    Draw the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axis on the graph paper.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_wzb3pvca">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_z7nw19qo">
                    Choose any starting point on the graph 
                    and label it as Point <m>A</m>. write down its coordinates.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_1x2fek7g">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_kq1f4lb1">
                    From Point <m>A</m>, move <m>6</m> units to the right parallel to 
                    the <m>x</m> axis and mark this new location as Point <m>B</m>. 
                    Write down its coordinates.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_ilovv92n">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_45pdo2r7">
                    Draw a directed line from point <m>A</m> to Point <m>B</m> to represent <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_36phuhii">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_j5ni4fae">
                    Find the midpoint of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and label it as Point <m>M</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_nqdgsndn">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qmj6tek1">
                    Identify the coordinates of Point <m>M</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_k6e1ajmh">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0vz418wq">
                    Think of a way to determine coordinates of Point <m>M</m> 
                    without manually counting the units.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_ieauyopw">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_71dtmuox">
                    Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_nzezyj2l">
        <p xml:id="auto_iq585l7k">
            Consider the cordinates of point <m>P</m> given as <m>(x_1,y_1)</m> 
            and point <m>N</m> given as <m>(x_2,y_2)</m> and <m>M</m>
            is the midpoint of <m>\mathbf{PN}</m> as shown in figure below.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="midpoint-vector-111">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="80%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                        \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (-7,-3) grid (9,8);

                        % Draw main grid (original)
                        \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (-7,-3) grid (9,8);

                        % Define points
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (P) at (-3,4);
                        \coordinate (N) at (3,4);
                        \coordinate (M) at (0,4);
                        
                        \node[below] at (O) {\small $\mathbf{O}$};
                        \node[left] at (P) {\small $\mathbf{P}(x_1,y_1)$};
                        \node[right] at (N) {\small $\mathbf{N}(x_2,y_2)$};
                        \node[above] at (M) {\small $\mathbf{M}$};
                        
                        \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (O) -- (-1.5,2) ;
                        \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (O) -- (1.5,2) ;
                        
                        % Draw vectors
                        \draw[thick] (O) -- (P) node[midway, left] {\large $\mathbf{a}$};
                        \draw[thick] (O) -- (N) node[midway, right] {\large $\mathbf{b}$};
                        \draw[thick] (N) -- (P);
                        \draw[thick] (O) -- (M);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p xml:id="auto_j9m8q8z0">
            <md>
                <mrow> \mathbf{OM} \amp = \mathbf{OP} + \mathbf{PM} </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  \mathbf{a} + \frac{1}{2} \mathbf{PN}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  \mathbf{a} + \frac{1}{2} (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  \mathbf{a} + \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{b} - \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{a}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  \mathbf{a}  - \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{a} + \frac{1}{2}\mathbf{b}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =  \frac{\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}}{2} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_6z6orf9f">
            But <m> \mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ y_1 \end{pmatrix}</m> and 
            <m> \mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} x_2 \\ y_2 \end{pmatrix}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0mj573n6">
            Thus, midpoint <m>\mathbf{M} = \left( \frac{ x_1 + x_2 }{ 2}, \frac{ y_1 + y_2 }{ 2}\right)</m>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students share their findings, formalise the midpoint concept and its vector derivation.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies — Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Misconception</cell>
                    <cell>Clarification</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Midpoint is just the distance between points.</cell>
                    <cell>The midpoint is a <em>point with coordinates</em>, not a distance.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>I just add the coordinates.</cell>
                    <cell>You add them, then <em>divide by 2</em> (take the average).</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>I only need to average the <m>x</m>-coordinates.</cell>
                    <cell>You must average both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates separately.</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>The formula only works for horizontal or vertical vectors.</cell>
                    <cell>It works for any vector in any direction.</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Work through the textbook example on the board, inviting students to supply each step.
            Then assign the practice exercises for independent or pair work.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_fruf27b6">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_95mphqkm">
                Find the coordinates of the midpoint <m>M</m> of <m>\textbf{AB}</m> given the following points 
               <m> A(6,1), \,\, B(4,3)</m>.
            </p>
            <!-- <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image> -->
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_bfutktra">
                To determine the midpoint <m>M</m> of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> , we apply the midpoint formulae as follows.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nxlnc7o3">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Midpoint } \amp = \left( \frac{x_1 + x_2}{2}, \frac{y_1 + y_2}{2}\right) </mrow>
                    <!-- <mrow>\text{ Substituting the given coordinates:} \amp </mrow> -->
                    <mrow> \amp =  \left(\frac{6 + 4}{2}, \frac{1+3}{2}\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \left(\frac{10}{2}, \frac{4}{2}\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \left(5, 2\right)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ir6jwuse">
                Thus, the coordinates of the midpoint <m>M</m> is <m>(5,2)</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
        <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The points <m>PQR</m> are on a straight line, given point <m>Q(-3,5)</m> is the midpoint of <m>PR</m>. Find the coordinates of <m>P</m> if <m>R(-10,15)</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We apply the midpoint formulae as follows.
            </p>
            <p>
                Midpoint <m>= (\frac{x_1 + x_2}{2} , \frac{y_1 + y_2}{2})</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(-3,5) = (\frac{x_1 - 10}{2} , \frac{y_1 + 15}{2})</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(x_1,y_1) = (4,-5)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                The point \;<m>P(4,-5)</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
